title.narrative: Low-achievement schools address violence and promote participatory, inclusive and quality education.

description.narrative: UNICEF Chile advocated with the Congress members and key actors of the education system to strengthen the public education system, and to promote inclusive and quality public education. UNICEF Chile focused its efforts to achieve SDGs through: Consolidation of the first National Public Education Strategy which affect more than 5,100 public schools with over 1,300,000 students; Promotion of an inclusive and positive school environment based on a formative approach; and Creation and implementation of a comprehensive and inclusive educational system to reduce school dropout and increase graduation rates in secondary education. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:20/01/2020

title.narrative: % of schools with school development plans in place that explicitly address equity issues.

baseline.value: There is no low achievement schools with articulated and sustained strategies to ensure effective inclusion and integral aspect of learning process.

target.value: 2020:20% of low achievement schools with articulated and sustained strategies to ensure effective inclusion and integral aspect of learning process.

actual.value: 2019:The change of education authorities in the second semester of 2018 changed the Government's priority in education and halted the design process of the National Public Education Strategy.

title.narrative: Existence of coordination mechanisms between low achievement schools and social protection local services.

baseline.value: There is no low achievement schools with explicit coordination mechanisms.

target.value: 2022:There is a coordination mechanism with local social protection services, validated and implemented in 3 municipalities with low achievement schools.
